WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.500
Hi everyone, my name is Kurt, and today I'll be going
over my network attached storage device — my home lab.

2
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.500
Basically, on my NAS I have TrueNAS running as the
operating system.

3
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:24.500
On the dashboard you can see some general information
here — the system information panel.

4
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:33.500
It's running the Community Edition of TrueNAS, which is
all free by the way. The version is 25.10.4.

5
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.500
You can see my hostname, the uptime being kept, and the
IP address right here — 192.168, so a local address on
my network.

6
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.500
Then you can see the CPU temperatures per core, and CPU
usage per core — it's not really using much, around 0%
average.

7
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:58.500
I'm running an i7, and I think the most I hit recently
was about 4%, right there.

8
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.500
Then on the right-hand side you can see memory and
storage.

9
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:13.500
Under memory we have 23.4 gigabytes total available.

10
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:24.500
Free memory available is 14.9 gigs. On the right-hand
side you'll see storage — about 23 terabytes, with
21.45 terabytes free.

11
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:33.500
On the left-hand side you can view a whole bunch of other
things — datasets, storage, virtual machines, apps.

12
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:41.500
There's a lot in here, but today we'll be going over just
the basics.

13
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:51.500
For the apps I have running, there are three implemented
here.

14
00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:01.500
I plan on implementing virtual machines as well, like
Kali Linux, to have more fun with. And on Jellyfin I have
my own media server.

15
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:09.500
It's free open source software. All three of these apps
are free — anyone can use this.

16
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.500
So if you're setting up a home lab, definitely worth
looking into.

17
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.500
Jellyfin is more like Netflix. Think of it like Disney
Plus, Netflix,

18
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:29.500
Hulu, Paramount Plus — all these apps you'd normally pay
a subscription for. You're doing all that for free.

19
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.500
Basically, you have your own MP4 files, your own media
files.

20
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:45.500
You go into Jellyfin, open the web user interface, and
it asks you for a login. After you log in, think of it
like Netflix.

21
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:53.500
You have any sort of media you want to watch — but
instead of a full catalog,

22
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:02.500
you use the files you already own, and watch them without
ads.

23
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:11.500
Any videos you already have, you can just watch them
through Jellyfin.

24
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:19.500
And on Nextcloud, I have my own cloud server — just like
Dropbox.

25
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.500
Any documents, videos, or files you want to put into your
own cloud server, that's what you use it for.

26
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.500
Except it's Nextcloud, and it's free.

27
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.500
On the right-hand side you can see general information,
notes, workloads, and application metadata.

28
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.500
Scroll down and you'll see a bit more general information
about the app. Same for the other two.

29
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:52.500
Any apps you implement, you'll see general information
about them. It's all free — go to truenas.com and check
the catalog.

30
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.500
Now if I go into Pi-hole and open the application info,
I'm going to open the web user interface and go a bit
more in depth,

31
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.500
since I implemented this fairly recently.

32
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.500
In Pi-hole you have total queries at the top, queries
blocked, the percentage blocked, and domains on list.

33
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:20.500
Pi-hole blocks ads and trackers from domains.

34
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:30.500
This is the main dashboard. If I scroll down, you'll see
clients and clients blocked.

35
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.500
You can see permitted and blocked domains here on the
right-hand side.

36
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.500
Honestly, a lot of the domains are fine — we don't have
to block that much.

37
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:49.500
But if I go into the query log and turn on live update,
it shows me in real time what's happening.

38
00:04:50.000 --> 00:05:01.500
It just keeps moving. Looks like it blocked two more from
Epic Games, and one from Microsoft.

39
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.500
We have a secure connection here from Cloudflare. A lot
of this is looking pretty good.

40
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:15.500
If I go to the second page, you can see

41
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:24.500
options to deny or allow access on the right-hand side.
So if something gets blocked and you want to allow it,

42
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.500
you just press allow on one of the red ones. And if
something is being allowed

43
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:41.500
that you want to block, you press deny. Let's go back and
look at

44
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.500
all the apps you can use on TrueNAS through their catalog.

45
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:54.500
You can see LLMs and AI software, and recently updated
apps — looks like they updated a smart home one, that's
interesting.

46
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:03.500
Authentication, single sign-on, backups, cameras,
databases, development, finance, fitness,

47
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:12.500
games — there's a lot in here. When you click one, it
shows you an install option.

48
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:23.500
Let's do the fitness one. If I go to Sparky Fitness and
press install, you'd open the web UI just like I did with
Pi-hole, and you're all set.

49
00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.500
I plan on implementing a lot more apps, but for my home
lab it's mostly these three for now,

50
00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:37.500
plus a local LLM running on my laptop through Ollama.

51
00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And that's mostly it for my home lab. Thanks for watching!
